<br>
You need the whole picture before you can make a long term commitment.<br>
<br>
Why play a Paladin?<br>
- If you've ever watched someone die and felt completely helpless to do someonething about it, you may enjoy playing a paladin. (Unlike other instant save abilities and spells, a paladin's are defensive so they are never resisted)<br>
- If you love to tank, but are willing to take a back seat to warriors on big encounters. Lets face it, against stunnable MOBs Paladins are the best tanks. Its only when CH or defensives come into play that a warrior really out shines us.<br>
- If you don't like complicated classes, you may enjoy being a Paladin. I might get flamed for saying so, but Paladins aren't a hard class to play (not the easiest like a wizard, but definately not hard). Paladins only have a few strategies to choose from, but lucky those few can be used in a lot of situations. Choosing what spells to mem is easy. When things go bad in a fight you're choices are root,stun, or heal, all usefull, if you can handle that you're halfway there.<br>
<br>
The cons to being a paladin <br>
- If you want damage output look elsewhere. Paladins aren't here to do damage. Its just not our thing. We are a melee class and thus can swing a sword, but if you're the type who's always comparing damage then you may want to pass this class up<br>
- If you hate seeking out specific pieces of equitment. If you hate camping for items and auctioning in EC, then this isn't a class for you. Paladins (like other tanks) are very equiptment dependant. This goes double for soloing, non-guilded Paladins.<br>
- If you like to get up and travel at a moments notice, pass this class up. Most paladins I know stay in zones where they can solo while waiting for a group to form. Personally I tend to stay in one location until a friend leads me someplace else. Paladins get no travel abilties other than Invis to Undead, which isn't even usefull in undead dungeons, thanks to live aggressive mobs in all of them.<br>
<br>
To be honest Paladins are in a unique position, they are the only effective melee+healers through most of the game. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvalyawanderfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Valya Wanderfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 740<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/5/02 2:34:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14724.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.pacbell.net/skfitz/valya.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> "If you don't like complicated classes, you may enjoy being a Paladin. I might get flamed for saying so, but Paladins aren't a hard class to play (not the easiest like a wizard, but definately not hard)"<br>
<br>
I have to agree and disagree.  I chose the paladin a long time ago partially for this reason, I was new to gaming and wanted something that would not be so hard to learn. :)   The spell choices are not so hard, and you certainly can get away with turning on autoattack and maybe slinging a heal or two between fights. But imo to be a really "good" paladin you have to pay attention all the time and be flexible with what you are doing. That's a big part of the fun for me. (PS this is NOT a flame on Cylria, I'm sure you play a "good" paladin, and I'm not disagreeing that our spell set is fairly basic).<br>
